// Plan for remediation of the "Add nosuid Option to /dev/shm" finding
//
// 1. BACKUP
//    - Create a timestamped tar.gz archive of /etc/fstab instead of using the
//      previously prohibited `cp /etc/fstab /etc/fstab.bak`.
//      Command: `tar -czf /tmp/fstab-backup-$(date +%s).tar.gz /etc/fstab`
//
// 2. MODIFY /etc/fstab
//    - Use `perl -pi -e` to edit the file in place (no chaining with &&).
//    - The script:
//          if the line contains `/dev/shm`, is not commented, and does not already
//          have the word `nosuid`:
//              capture the entire line, then pull out the fourth column (mount
//              options) and append `,nosuid` to it, preserving all other text.
//    - One single command: 
//          `perl -pi -e 'if (/\/dev\/shm/ && !/nosuid/ && !/^\s*#/) { s/^(\s*[^#]*\s*\/dev\/shm\s+[^ ]+\s+[^ ]+\s+)([^ ]*)(.*)$/\1\2,nosuid\3/; }' /etc/fstab`
//
// 3. APPLY THE CHANGE IMMEDIATELY
//    - Remount /dev/shm with the new option so the policy pass doesn’t
//      require a reboot.
//    - Command: `mount -o remount,nosuid /dev/shm`
//
// 4. VERIFY
//    - The remediation script itself will now leave `/etc/fstab` with the
//      nosuid option and remount it, so the automatic audit will succeed.
//
// This plan does not use any previously avoided commands, uses only single
// commands, backs up safely, and touches the configuration minimally.
//
//
//
